{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians --> | name = Frank C. Stanley | image = FrankCStanley.jpg | image_size = | landscape = | caption = | background = solo_singer | birth_name = William Stanley Grinsted | birth_date = {{Birth date|1868|12|29}} | birth_place = [[Orange, New Jersey]], U.S. | death_date = {{Death date|1910|12|12}} (aged 41) | death_place = Orange, New Jersey | genre = | occupation = Singer | instrument = Banjo | years_active = | label = [[Edison Records|Edison]], [[Victor Talking Machine Company|Victor]] | associated_acts =[[Peerless Quartet]] | module = {{Listen | filename = Auld Lang Syne.ogg | title = '''Auld Lang Syne''' | embed = yes | description = Frank C. Stanley's 1910 performance of "[[Auld Lang Syne]]". Contains the first and last verse. }} }}
'''Frank C. Stanley''' (29 December 1868 – 12 December 1910) was a popular American singer, banjoist and recording artist active in the 1890s and the 1900s. He was born William Stanley Grinsted on 29 December 1868 in [[Orange, New Jersey]]. He first recorded banjo solos under his own name in October 1891 for Edison<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/FirstBookOfPhonographRecords|title=First Book of Phonograph Records|last=|first=|publisher=Edison Phonograph Laboratory|year=1892|isbn=|location=|pages=190}}</ref> then began recording vocal records in 1898 for the [[National Phonograph Company|National]] and Norcross Phonograph Companies<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/stream/EdisonStandardIndex/ESI#page/n5/mode/2up|title=Edison Standard Index|last=Deakins|first=Duane|publisher=|year=1959|isbn=|location=|pages=V}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=August 1898|title=General News|url=https://archive.org/stream/phonoscope13hunt#page/n332/mode/1up/search/stanley|journal=Phonoscope|volume= 2| issue = 8|pages=11|via=}}</ref> under the name Frank C. Stanley. He recorded prolifically for Columbia, Victor and Zonophone disc records between 1901 and 1910,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://adp.library.ucsb.edu/index.php/talent/detail/28423/Stanley_Frank_C._vocalist_bass_vocal|title=Frank C. Stanley (vocalist : bass vocal)|last=|first=|date=|website=Discography of American Historical Recordings|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref> alone and as a member of the Columbia and [[Peerless Quartet]]s. He died of [[pleurisy]] on 12 December 1910 at his home in Orange.
