'''Henri Robin''' (1811–1874), born '''Henrik Joseph Donckel''', was a French illusionist, born in [[Hazebrouck]]. In the early 1850s, he performed at [[Windsor Castle]], at the request of [[Queen Victoria]]. In 1861, he became the first illusionist to offer a full programme of magic at [[Egyptian Hall]] in London. Between 1862 and 1869, he managed a theatre in the [[Boulevard du Temple]], Paris. His most well-known illusion in these years was "The Medium of Inkerman", in which a drum on stage was apparently struck by an unseen spirit, in response to questions from the audience.<ref name=Stanton/>

