{{good article}}
{{italic title}}
The '''''{{IAST|Mānasollāsa}}''''', also known as '''''Abhilashitartha Chintamani''''', is an early 12th-century Sanskrit text composed by the [[Kalyani Chalukya dynasty|Kalyani Chalukya]] king [[Someshvara III]], who ruled in present-day [[South India]]. It is an encyclopedic work covering topics such as polity, governance, ethics, economics, astronomy, astrology, rhetoric, veterinary medicine, horticulture, perfumes, food, architecture, sports, painting, poetry and music. The text is a valuable source of socio-cultural information on 11th- and 12th-century India.

The encyclopedic treatise is structured as five sub-books with a cumulative total of 100 chapters. It is notable for its extensive discussion of arts, particularly music and dance. It is also notable for including chapters on food recipes and festivals, many of which are a part of modern Indian culture.

Another medieval era Sanskrit text with the title ''Mānasollāsa'' also exists, consisting of devotional praise hymns (''[[stotra]]''), and it is different from the encyclopedic treatise.

== Nomenclature ==
{{Quote box |width=26em | bgcolor=#FFE0BB |align=right |salign = right
|quote=[[File:Fish icon (The Noun Project 27052).svg|30px]] '''12th century fish recipe'''
<poem>
Cut fishes into pieces and wash them well.
Cook along with tamarind juice.
Sprinkle well with wheat flour. Fry in heated oil till brown.
Add rock salt. Sprinkle powdered cardamom and pepper.
</poem>
|source =—''Manasollasa'' 3.1530–1531<ref name=sadhalenenefish177 />}}
The title ''Manasollasa'' (मानसोल्लास) is a compound Sanskrit word, consisting of ''manas'' ( मनस्) or "mind" and ''ullasa'' (उल्लास) or "rejoicing, delighting".<ref>[http://spokensanskrit.de/index.php?beginning=0+&tinput=sollasa&trans=Translate Sollasa], Sanskrit-English Dictionary, Koeln University, Germany (2012)</ref> It means "the joy, delighter or entertainer of the mind".{{Sfn|Datta|1988|p=1165}}{{Sfn|McHugh|2012|p=118}} Alternatively, the compound word can be broken as ''manasa'' and ''ullasa'', which mean "happiness of mind".<ref>Nalini Sadhale and YL Nene (2010), Bhudharakrida (Royal Enjoyment on a Pleasure-mound) in Manasollasa, Asian Agri-History, Vol. 14, No. 4, pages 319–335</ref><ref>[http://spokensanskrit.de/index.php?beginning=0+&tinput=+ullasa&trans=Translate Ullasa], Sanskrit-English Dictionary, Koeln University, Germany (2012)</ref>

The work is divided into five sub-books suffixed as Viṁśati (vinshati, विंशति) which means 20 and refers to the 20 chapters in the sub-book.<ref>[http://spokensanskrit.de/index.php?beginning=0+&tinput=viMzati+&trans=Translate viMzati], Sanskrit-English Dictionary, Koeln University, Germany (2012)</ref> In modern scholarship, it is referred by [[IAST]] spellings "Manasollāsa",{{Sfn|Banerji|1989|p=238}} and "Mānasollāsa".{{Sfn|McHugh|2012|pp=154–155}}

It is also known as the ''Abhilashitartha Chintamani'' ({{IAST|Abhilaṣitārtha Cintāmaṇi}}) (literally, the precious gem that fulfills wish).{{Sfn|Kincaid|Parasanisa|1918|pp=32–33}}{{Sfn|Datta|1988|p=1165}} This text title is spelled ''Manasollāsa'',{{Sfn|Banerji|1989|p=238}} and there is another medieval era Indian text with the title, ''Mānasollāsa'' ({{lang-sa|मानसोल्लास}}), written in [[Stotra]] (poetry of praise) style related to [[Dakshinamurthy|Dakshinamurti]], very different in scope and attributed to [[Adi Shankara]] or Suresvara.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/Dakshinamurti.Stotra.of.Sri.Sankaracharya.with.Commentaries/Dakshinamurti.Stotra.of.Sri.Sankaracharya.with.Commentaries.by.Suresvaracharya.Swayamprakasa.Ramatirtha#page/n0/mode/2up Dakshinamurti Stotra], A Mahadeva Sastri (1895), see Preface section</ref>

== Date and author ==
The text was completed in 1129 CE by Someshvara III. He became the king in 1127,{{Sfn|Kincaid|Parasanisa|1918|pp=32–33}} was part of the Kalyani Chalukya dynasty, and the third king in this dynasty. The year when he succeeded to the throne is approximate, and some scholars state it to be 1125 CE.{{Sfn|Scharfe|1989|p=24}} The author hailed from the medieval [[Deccan Plateau|Deccan region]] consisting of large parts of modern [[Karnataka]], [[Telangana]], western [[Andhra Pradesh]] and southern [[Maharashtra]].<ref name=sadhalenenefish177>Nalini Sadhale and YL Nene (2005), On Fish in Manasollasa (c. 1131 AD), ''Asian Agri-History'', Vol. 9, No. 3, pages 177–199</ref>

Epigraphical evidence suggests that the dynasty made numerous land grants and financial awards to the causes of [[Shaivism]] and monastic scholarship.{{Sfn|Reddy|2014|pp=99–101}} These monasteries in the [[Indian peninsula]] became centers of the study of the [[Vedas]] and [[Hindu philosophy|Hindu philosophies]] such as the [[Nyaya]] school.{{Sfn| Reddy|2014|pp=99–101}} Someshvara III composed this text in the initial years of his kingship.{{Sfn|Banerji|1989|p=238}}

== Structure ==
{{Quote box |width=26em | bgcolor=#FFE0BB |align=right |salign = right
|quote=[[File:Elephant profil.svg|30px]] '''Veterinary care for [[Elephants]]'''
<poem>
All those diseases of elephants caused by [[Dosha|''Vata'' and ''Pitta'']] are cured without fail, by a mixture of ''[[Tinospora cordifolia|Guduchi]]'', two types of ''[[Merremia emarginata|Parnika]]'', two types of ''[[Polygonatum verticillatum|Meda]]'', ''[[Malaxis acuminta|Jivaka]]'' and ''[[Malaxis muscifera|Rishabha]]'', two types of ''[[Fritillaria cirrhosa|Kakoli]]'', ''[[Withania somnifera|Ashvagandha]]'', ''[[Ipomoea digitata|Vidari]]'' and ''[[Asparagus racemosus|Shatavari]]'', either in powder, paste, or decoction form.
</poem>
|source =—''Manasollasa'' 2.649–650<ref name=sadhaleneneelephant>Nalini Sadhale and YL Nene (2004), On Elephants in Manasollasa – 2. Diseases and Treatment, ''Asian Agri-History'' Vol. 8, No. 2, pages 115–127</ref>}}
The ''Manasollasa'' encyclopedic treatise was written in Sanskrit in  [[Kannada language|Kannada]] speaking region  of India. The encyclopedia is in poetic verse style.{{Sfn|Datta|1988|p=1165}}{{Sfn|Banerji|1989|p=238}}

It is structured into five sub-books and cumulatively contains 100 chapters. The five ''Vinshatis'' (sub-book of 20s) are ''Rājyaprāptikāraṇa'', ''Rājyasya Sthairyakāraṇa'', ''Bhartur Upabhogakāraṇa'', ''Pramoda kāraṇa'' and the ''Krīḍā viṁśati.''{{Sfn|Banerji|1989|p=238}}{{Sfn|Udgaonkar|1986|p=25}} Each chapter deals with a specific topic, ranging from gaining a kingdom, its governance, economics, infrastructure, architecture, medicine,{{Sfn|Joshi|Hebbali|2004}} cuisine, ornaments, perfumery and love-games,{{Sfn|McHugh|2012|pp=118, 131–133}} sports, jewelry, painting, music and dance.{{Sfn|Datta|1988|p=1165}}{{Sfn|Banerji|1989|p=238}}{{Sfn| Shrigondekar|1961|p=vi}} A major part of the text is dedicated to music and musical instruments, with 2500 verses dedicated to it.{{Sfn|Banerji|1989|p=238}}

The number of ''{{IAST|śloka}}s'' in this work are:

{| class="wikitable"
! style="background: #ffad66;" | Twenty-book{{Sfn|Udgaonkar|1986|p=25}}<br />({{IAST|Viṁśati}})
! style="background: #ffad66;" | Chapters<br />({{IAST|Adhyāya}})
! style="background: #ffad66;" | Verses<br />({{IAST|Śloka}})
|-
| I. {{IAST|''Rājyaprāptikāraṇa''}}
